          question: 'Write a Flask route function get_employees() mounted on GET /api/employees:\n- Accepts query parameters: department (optional), page (default 1), per_page (default 10)\n- Filters from a global list EMPLOYEES (list of dicts)\n- Returns JSON: {"data": paginated employee list, "total": total count, "page": current page, "per_page": items per page}\n(Only write the route function — assume app and EMPLOYEES already exist)',
          starterCode: 'from flask import Flask, request, jsonify\n\n# Assume app = Flask(__name__) is already created\n# Assume EMPLOYEES = [{"id": 1, "name": "...", "department": "..."}] already exists\n\n@app.route("/api/employees", methods=["GET"])\ndef get_employees():\n    # Get query parameters\n    # Filter and paginate\n    # Return JSON\n    pass',
          expectedQuery: 'from flask import Flask, request, jsonify\n\n@app.route("/api/employees", methods=["GET"])\ndef get_employees():\n    department = request.args.get("department")\n    page = request.args.get("page", 1, type=int)\n    per_page = request.args.get("per_page", 10, type=int)\n    filtered = EMPLOYEES\n    if department:\n        filtered = [e for e in EMPLOYEES if e["department"] == department]\n    total = len(filtered)\n    start = (page - 1) * per_page\n    end = start + per_page\n    return jsonify({\n        "data": filtered[start:end],\n        "total": total,\n        "page": page,\n        "per_page": per_page,\n    })',
